{"add":{"doc":{"id":"e61ba4af65ce7b38bd47727ac1ab3d2a69b7061ab603912945f58785a6c0f1a3","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/61/Theatre_and_Concert_Hall%2C_Esplanade_%E2%80%93_Theatres_on_the_Bay%2C_Singapore_-_20110528.jpg/220px-Theatre_and_Concert_Hall%2C_Esplanade_%E2%80%93_Theatres_on_the_Bay%2C_Singapore_-_20110528.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Since the 1990s, the government has been promoting Singapore as a centre for arts and culture, in particular the performing arts, and to transform the country into a cosmopolitan \"gateway between the East and West\".[228] One highlight was the construction of Esplanade – Theatres on the Bay, a performing arts centre opened in October 2002.[229] The national orchestra, Singapore Symphony Orchestra, plays at the Esplanade. The annual Singapore Arts Festival is organised by the National Arts Council. The stand-up comedy scene has been growing, with a weekly open mic.[230] Singapore hosted the 2009 Genée International Ballet Competition, a classical ballet competition promoted by London's Royal Academy of Dance.[231]"]}}}